04819nam a22007815i 9781501757730DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017577307 a10.1515/97815017577302doi  a(DE-B1597)572362  a(OCoLC)1224278756  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aN7626b.M33 2018eb 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a940.52231 aMcCallum, Claire, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Fate of the New Man :bRepresenting and Reconstructing Masculinity in Soviet Visual Culture, 1945–1965 /cClaire McCallum. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (324 p.) :b14 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. THE LIVING -- t2. THE DAMAGED -- t3. THE DEAD -- t4. HOMECOMINGS -- t5. FATHERHOOD AFTER FATHER STALIN -- tCONCLUSION -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1945 and 1965, the catastrophe of war—and the social and political changes it brought in its wake—had a major impact on the construction of the Soviet masculine ideal. Drawing upon a wide range of visual material, The Fate of the New Man traces the dramatic changes in the representation of the Soviet man in the postwar period. It focuses on the two identities that came to dominate such depictions in the two decades after the end of the war: the Soviet man's previous role as a soldier and his new role in the home once the war was over. In this compelling study, Claire McCallum focuses on the reconceptualization of military heroism after the war, the representation of contentious subjects such as the war-damaged body and bereavement, and postwar changes to the depiction of the Soviet man as father. McCallum shows that it was the Second World War, rather than the process of de-Stalinization, that had the greatest impact on the masculine ideal, proving that even under the constraints of Socialist Realism, the physical and emotional devastation caused by the war was too great to go unacknowledged. The Fate of the New Man makes an important contribution to Soviet masculinity studies. McCallum's research also contributes to broader debates surrounding the impact of Stalin's death on Soviet society and on the nature of the subsequent Thaw, as well as to those concerning the relationship between Soviet culture and the realities of Soviet life. This fascinating study will appeal to scholars and students of Soviet history, masculinity studies, and visual culture studies.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArtzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aFathers in art. 0aMasculinity in popular culture. 0aMasculinityzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aMen in art. 0aMen in popular culture. 0aSoldiers in art. 4aArt History. 4aGender Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  amen in Soviet Union, Soviet masculinity, Soviet military, Socialist Realism, Stalin's death, post-WWII Soviet Union.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175773040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501757730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501757730/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPD